body:
@kevinsawicki thanks for your reply.

> Is it only the Tab key that isn't working for you? Is your page not receiving the event or is the event data just wrong/incomplete?

Yes, it's only the tab key. The page does receive a keyboard event as expected but `keyCode: 'Tab'` seems to be ignored in 1.4.0 and above.

Basically, I have an on-screen QWERTY keyboard which allows users to input their info into 2 input fields. All keys work as expected in Electron 1.4.2 except the tab key. In 1.3.7, the tab key works.

In my project, the tab key should mimic the tab key on the physical keyboard to set the focus from one field to the next.

Taking cues from your response, I've put together a simple test to demonstrate this:

``` js
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title></title>
    <style>
      webview {
        position: absolute;
        top: 0;
        left: 0;
        right: 0;
        bottom: 0
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <webview src="http://purplemass.com/temp/electron-test.html" />
    <script>
    webView = document.querySelector('webview');

    webView.addEventListener("dom-ready", function(event) {
      // webView.openDevTools();
      webViewContent = webView.getWebContents();

      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'char', keyCode: 'A'});
      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'char', keyCode: 'B'});

      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'keyDown', keyCode: 'Tab'});
      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'char', keyCode: ''});

      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'char', keyCode: 'C'});
      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'char', keyCode: 'D'});
      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'char', keyCode: 'E'});

      webViewContent.sendInputEvent({ type: 'keyDown', keyCode: 'Backspace'});
    });

    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

The above code puts **AB** into **input1** and **CD** into **input2** in Electron 1.3.7.

In 1.4.2, I get **ABCD** in **input1**.

It's interesting to note that when a key is pressed on a physical keyboard, the keyboard event contains `event.key`, `event.code` and `event.keyCode`. Using Electron's `sendInputEvent`, `event.key` and `event.code` are empty but I think this is the expected behaviour.
